Preheat your #oven{} to 200°C. Chop the @salad potatoes{350%g} into 2cm chunks
(no need to peel) and pop on a #baking tray{}. Cut the @fennel{1} in half
lengthways, remove the triangle root in the middle, then quarter lengthways.
Put on another baking tray. Drizzle both with @oil{drizzle} and season with
@salt{} and @pepper{}. Toss to coat then spread out and roast in your oven
(potatoes on the top shelf, fennel on the middle) until golden, ~{25-30%minutes},
turning halfway through.

Meanwhile, halve the @baby plum tomatoes{125}. Zest and halve the @lemon{1}.
Roughly chop the @dill{1/2%bunch}(roughly chopped, stalks and all). Cut the
@unsalted butter{60%g} into small pieces. When you turn the fennel, add the
tomatoes to the tray, drizzle with @white wine vinegar{15%ml} and return to
the oven for the remaining cooking time.

Put a #small saucepan{} of water on to boil to cook the samphire later (don't
add any salt - the samphire is salty enough!). Put the @monkfish medallions{200%g}
on a #plate{} and pat dry with #kitchen paper{}. Season on both sides with salt
and pepper.

IMPORTANT: Remember to wash your hands after handling raw fish.

When the potatoes and veg have about 10 mins left, heat a drizzle of oil in a
#large frying pan{} on high heat. When hot, add the monkfish pieces.

Cook the monkfish pieces for ~{3%minutes} each side, adjusting the heat as
necessary. IMPORTANT: The monkfish is cooked when opaque in the centre. When
cooked, transfer to a plate and set aside. When you turn the monkfish, drop
the @samphire{40%g} into the boiling water and cook for ~{3%minutes} before
draining in a #sieve{}. Return to the pan (off the heat) with the lid on to
keep warm.

Turn the heat to low, then add the lemon juice to the #frying pan{} and gradually
stir in the butter until melted and combined. Stir in half the dill - this is
your sauce! Return the monkfish to the sauce and turn to coat, remove from the
heat. When the potatoes are cooked, sprinkle over the lemon zest and toss to
coat. Get ready to serve.

Divide the roasted new potatoes, fennel and tomatoes between your plates.
Arrange the monkfish medallions next to the potatoes, then scatter over the
samphire. Spoon over the lemon butter sauce and finish with a sprinkling of the
remaining dill. Enjoy!

> This dish is perfect for impressing guests with its delicate and elegant flavours.
> The samphire provides a distinctive crisp and salty flavour that complements
> the meaty texture of the monkfish beautifully.